  "text": "Normalized tension values were plotted against a range of pCa to construct the pCa-tension relations (Fig. 5,  A and B) . The pCa-tension relation of -MHC + RcTnT 1-43 was shifted to the right of -MHC + RcTnT WT (Fig. 5 A) , indicating a desensitization of myofilament Ca 2+ sensitivity (pCa 50 ) in -MHC + RcTnT 1-43 fibers. This rightward shift of the pCa-tension relation was ablated in -MHC + RcTnT 1-43 fibers (indicated by arrows in Fig. 5 B) , suggesting that -MHC counteracted the desensitizing effect of RcTnT 1-43 on pCa 50 . Two-way ANOVA revealed a significant interaction effect (P < 0.05) on pCa 50 , suggesting that -and -MHC isoforms divergently affected the way RcTnT 1-43 and RcTnT 44-73 altered pCa 50 (Fig. 5, C and D) . The main contributing decreased pCa 50 significantly in -MHC fibers, an effect that was counteracted in -MHC fibers. Number of determinations was at least seven for each group. Values are reported as mean ± SEM. ***, P < 0.001. [CITATION_1] . Therefore, we sought to determine if the impact of -and -MHC on XB detachment kinetics had any effect on how RcTnT 1-43 and RcTnT 44-73 modulated contractile dynamics. The rate of XB distortion dynamics (c) was measured by fitting the NLRD model to force responses elicited by step-like ML perturbations [CITATION_2] . Two-way ANOVA showed no significant interaction effect but revealed a significant main effect of -and -MHC on c. Post-hoc multiple comparisons showed that c decreased in all groups of -MHC-containing fibers when compared with the corresponding groups of -MHC-containing fibers. However, RcTnT 1-43 and RcTnT 44-73 did not alter c in -or -MHC fibers (Table 1) .",
